            <p class="text-body text-sm font-sans leading-relaxed">UUIDs are designed to be unique across space and time. UUID v4 has 2^122 possible values &mdash; the probability of collision is extremely low. UUID v1 uses timestamps and node identifiers to guarantee uniqueness within a system. UUID v7 combines timestamps with random bits, making collisions practically impossible under normal usage. All versions are safe for production use as database primary keys, distributed system identifiers, or API resource IDs.</p>
